  <h2>Ask your pharmacist first</h2>
  <p>Your pharmacist is an expert in medicines and can answer many questions without you needing an appointment with us. They can advise on:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Side effects of your medication</li>
    <li>Whether your medication is safe to take with others</li>
    <li>How and when to take your medication</li>
    <li>Over-the-counter treatments for common conditions</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Pharmacists are available in person at your local pharmacy, and many offer a private consultation area.</p>

  <h2>Contact us</h2>
  <p>If your query cannot be answered by a pharmacist, or you have a concern about your prescribed treatment, please contact us:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Telephone:</strong> <a href="tel:{{ site.phone | replace(' ', '') }}">{{ site.phone }}</a> — Monday to Friday, 08:00 to 18:00</li>
    <li><strong>Email:</strong> <a href="mailto:{{ site.email }}">{{ site.email }}</a></li>
  </ul>
  <p>Please do not email urgent medical queries. If you are concerned about a reaction to medication, call us or NHS 24 on 111.</p>

  <h2>Changing or stopping medication</h2>
  <p>Do not stop taking prescribed medication without speaking to a clinician first. If you'd like to discuss your medication, book an appointment or call us during opening hours.</p>

  <h2>Prescribing policies</h2>

  <h3>Medicines requiring monitoring</h3>
  <p>Some medicines can only be issued on an ongoing basis if regular monitoring tests (such as blood tests) are kept up to date. If your monitoring is overdue, we may not be able to issue your prescription until the relevant tests have been completed. You will be contacted if this applies to you.</p>

  <h3>Travelling abroad with medication</h3>
  <p>If you are going abroad for up to three months, we can supply your repeat medication for the duration of your trip. Patients who remain abroad longer than three months may be removed from our registered list and will need to register with a GP in the country they are living in. If you plan to travel with controlled drugs, contact the Home Office for guidance on import/export certificates.</p>

  <h3>Benzodiazepines and flight anxiety</h3>
  <p>We are unable to prescribe diazepam or other benzodiazepines solely to manage anxiety about flying. Evidence shows that benzodiazepines can impair your ability to respond to emergencies on board, and their use is discouraged by aviation authorities. If you have concerns about flying, the following resources may help:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="https://www.flyandbecalm.com/" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fly and Be Calm</a> — online course for fear of flying</li>
    <li>British Airways <em>Flying with Confidence</em> course</li>
    <li>Virgin Atlantic <em>Flying Without Fear</em> course</li>
  </ul>
  <p>You are also welcome to speak with your GP at a routine appointment if you would like to discuss anxiety management more broadly.</p>

  <h2>NHS Inform — medication advice</h2>
  <p><a href="https://www.nhsinform.scot/tests-and-treatments/medicines-and-medical-aids/medicines/" rel="noopener noreferrer">NHS Inform</a> has reliable information about many common medicines, including what they're used for and possible side effects.</p>

